[6] Cholera - DR Congo (Katanga)
Date: Sat 10 Dec 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: YodayOnline.com [edited]
<http://www.todayonline.com/articles/89325.asp>

8 reported dead in DR Congo cholera outbreak
--------------------------------------------
At least 8 people have died in a cholera outbreak in Katanga province in
the south east of the Democratic Republic of Congo, the charity Medecins
sans Frontieres (MSF -- Doctors without Borders) reported. "We have
registered 50 cases in 2 weeks at Kabalo, which have resulted in 7 deaths
up to today," Diego Cameno, general coordinator of MSF-Spain, told AFP. "In
the area around the town, at least 2 cases have been reported and one death
registered."
The area is a conflict zone where the army has launched an operation
against local militias. "The epidemic is progressing very rapidly," Cameno
said. "We have a team at Kabalo backing up the main hospital and the
surrounding pharmacies and taking care of health emergencies, but the
problem is getting to the patients" in a zone where Mai Mai militias are
active.
Violence carried out by armed groups and fighting between them and
government forces have led to the displacement of about 36 000 people in
Nord-Katanga, according to the World Food Program, of whom about 3000 are
in the Kabolo area.
Humanitarian agencies have practically no access to displaced people in the
combat area and cannot organize convoys in militia-controlled districts
because of a lack of security.
******
[7] Cholera - Myanmar (Madalay Division)
Date: Thu 8 Dec 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Democratic Voice of Burma [edited]
<http://english.dvb.no/news.php?id=6110>

Cholera outbreaks in upper Burma Kyaukpandaung kill at least 4
--------------------------------------------------------------
Cholera outbreaks within the previous months at Taungbetletpyin-nyaung and
Zeegone Villages, Kyaukpandaung Township, Mandalay Division in upper
central Burma, killed at least 4 people, it has emerged. A local resident
told DVB that there have been no preventative measures from the authorities
and that staff from the government health department had made no concerted
efforts to treat the victims or attempted to stem the outbreak. He added
that the villagers could not protect themselves from the epidemic because
of dire poverty, as they could not even buy necessary basic medicines.
******
[8] Diarrhea - Philippines (Samar)
Date: Mon 12 Dec 2005
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: Manila Standard [edited]
<http://www.manilastandardtoday.com/?page=news07_dec13_2005>

Contaminated wells cause diarrhea outbreak in Samar
---------------------------------------------------
The Department of Health (DOH) on Mon 12 Dec 2005 said that contaminated
deep wells may have caused an outbreak of diarrhea in Guian, Eastern Samar,
which left 3 residents dead and at least 302 people affected.
Eric Tayag, head of the DOH's National Epidemiology Center, told ANC that
the diarrhea outbreak that started in October 2005 was caused by dirty
water from deep wells. Tayag said that residents have been advised to boil
the water taken from wells and faucets before drinking.
He said that 3 residents of the affected barangays have already died of
diarrhea, while at least 302 people are still being treated. Most of the
victims were children between the ages of one to 14. Tayag also said that
the DOH regional office and the provincial government of Eastern Samar have
already sent medicine and chlorine tablets to Guian.
Luz Pimentel, surveillance officer of Filipe Abrigo Memorial Hospital,
earlier said that the diarrhea was 1st reported in Barangay Bungtod in
Guian. The disease later spread to 42 other barangays of Guian, she added.
******
[9] Dysentery, flood related - Sri Lanka
Date: Tue 6 Dec 2005
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: The Daily News, Sri Lanka [edited]
<http://www.dailynews.lk/2005/12/07/news24.htm>

Dysentery on the rise in wake of floods
---------------------------------------
Health authorities yesterday, 5 Dec 2005, warned that the number of
patients affected by dysentery had increased over the last few days
following torrential rains and flood situations in many parts of the
country. The number of patients affected by dysentery has topped 160. The
number of dysentery cases island-wide stood at 101 as of last Fri 2 Dec 2005.
"The highest number of dysentery cases are reported from Kurunegala (77)
and Matale (32), while Puttalam also had recorded 12 cases," a Ministry
spokesman told the Daily News. Besides, a significant number of cases are
reported from Kandy, Dehiwala, Tirncomalee and Hipalogama in Anuradhapura.
Health officials attributed this increase to the pollution of water due to
the flood condition experienced during the last week. "Excreta has found
its way into drinking water, leading to high level of pollution." Officials
requested the public to drink boiled water only and desist from consuming
raw vegetables, especially leafy vegetables, for some time to prevent the
spread of disease.
[byline: Bharatha Malawaraarachchi]
******
[10] Diarrhea, deaths - Philippines (Cantanduanes)
Date: Tue 6 Dec 2005
From: Alfonso Rodriguez <ajrm_msds@yahoo.es>
Source: ABS CBN News, Philippines [edited]
<http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/storypage.aspx?StoryId=24094>

Diarrhea claims 3 lives in Catanduanes
--------------------------------------
3 people died of diarrhea in Barangay Cogon in Virac, Catanduanes,
prompting the Department of Health (DOH) to investigate the cause of an
apparent outbreak among other residents, ANC reported Tue 6 Dec 2005.
Dr Ferchito Avelino, assistant regional health director in Bicol, said the
cases could be related to a similar incident reported in the municipalities
of San Andres and Virac in September 2005. "There were 14 confirmed deaths
in San Andres and Virac [in September 2005] which were caused by water
sources contaminated by _E. coli_ bacteria," Avelino said.
At least 70 other residents in Cogon were taken to hospitals after showing
symptoms of the disease. The apparent outbreak was 1st reported on 30 Nov
2005. A 4 person team from the DOH has been sent to the barangay to
investigate the spread of diarrhea.
******
[11] Diarrhea, volcano evacuees - Vanuata (Ambae Island)
Date: Mon 12 Dec 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: XinHuaNet.com [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-12/12/content_3910424.htm>

Diarrhea hits Vanuatu volcano evacuation camp
---------------------------------------------
Diarrhea has hit some people in an evacuation camp on South Pacific Vanuatu
after a volcano began erupting, according to the Monday, 12 Dec 2005,
report from Ambae Island, Vanuatu.
Around 5000 evacuees were moved on Ambae Island last weekend after Mt
Manaro began erupting sulfur gas and ash up to 3000 meters above this
island of 10 000 villagers in northern Vanuatu. Aid staff said they
received reports of diarrhea in the evacuation camps. After checking with
the health nurse at the center, "there are a few people with these diseases."
Villagers used to living in huts built from palm fronds and sheets of tin
in the cool jungles on the volcano's flanks are now crowded into hot
concrete block buildings close to the shore.
******
[12] Dysentery - Russia (Ryazanskaya)
Date: Mon 12 Dec 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Itar-Tass [edited]
<http://www.itar-tass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=2713657&PageNum=0>

Over 300 hospitalized with suspected dysentery in Ryazan region
---------------------------------------------------------------
Over 300 residents of the Kasimov city in Russia's Ryazan region have been
hospitalized with an acute intestinal infection. Dysentery has been
confirmed in 97 cases, the head of the regional department of the
Rospotrebnadzor consumer rights watchdog told Itar-Tass on Mon 12 Dec 2005.
7 people have fallen ill over the past 24 hours, Larisa Sarayeva said. An
outbreak of dysentery has been registered in several districts of the city.
Criminal proceedings have been launched, city prosecutor Yevgeny Popov
said. Samples of products from several supermarkets have been sent for lab
tests.
